eriod, the volume begins a crucial rethinking of social and cultural life under Communist regimes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aJudaism, Jews, Jewish people, Communism, Socialism, Jewish studies, sociology, Soviet bloc, USSR, Soviet Union, Cold War, Europe: Israel, Holocaust, state policy, religion, American, United States, USA, Poland, Czechoslovakia, Eastern European, Central Europe, regimes, government, secular, secularism, identity, Jewish identity, history, Hungary, East Germany, Germany.1 aBohus, Kata, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCapková, Katerina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCapková, Katerina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDumitru, Diana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDymshits, Valery, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEstraikh, Gennady, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKijek, Kamil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKijek, Kamil, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKoch, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaksimowska, Agata, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShneer, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShternshis, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSilber, Marcos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStach, Stephan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZelenina, Galina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aČapková, Kateřina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.